"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445815","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-01","<p>Landowners are free to choose any legal method to control grey squirrels on their own land and to choose the methods they believe to be most effective and appropriate in any location. However, Forestry Commission England currently considers that free shooting has limited effectiveness in controlling grey squirrel populations, with better, more effective methods often available. In addition, the majority of the public forest estate has unrestricted public access and public safety is of paramount importance. For these reasons the Commission does not allow the shooting of grey squirrels by volunteers on its land. Volunteers are, nevertheless, an essential part of controlling grey squirrels and control methodologies continue to be developed and evaluated against the criteria of efficacy, safety and animal welfare. The Commission is additionally encouraging improvements to other methods of control including trapping, as well as assessing the findings of a recent study from Ireland which suggested that an increased pine marten population may result in a reduced grey squirrel population.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission is seriously concerned about the negative impact of grey squirrel populations on woodland and specifically on native woodland. The Government is committed to pursuing co-ordinated action at a national level and in conjunction with partners through the Squirrel Accord, to which both Defra and Forestry Commission England are signatories. Work is continuing to improve the effectiveness of control methods; the structure of grants has been changed to support grey squirrel control and substantial work continues with partners to support our red squirrel populations, including through the control of grey squirrels. The Commission is open to further engagement with national and local organisations as well as landowners sharing our commitment to grey squirrel control for the protection of woodland and red squirrel populations.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-02-01T15:52:56.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445815/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445815/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-19","Squirrels: Pest Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Forestry Commission refuses to allow the use of air rifles by experienced, trained, and insured volunteers as part of an integrated programme for grey squirrel control.","false","Biography information for Lord Inglewood",,"Lord Inglewood","HL5225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445835","Attorney General","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not maintain a central record of the number of prosecutions brought under the Fraud Act 2006. However, records are held showing the overall number of offences charged in which a prosecution commenced in the magistrates’ courts (the distinction being that some prosecutions involved multiple offences). These figures are detailed in the following table:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of offences charged under the Fraud Act 2006 in which a prosecution commenced in the magistrates’ court*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>27,759</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>29,592</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>28,164</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>26,581</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>25,832</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>26,113</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>* Data Source: CPS management information system</em></p><br /><p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) investigates and, where appropriate, prosecutes the topmost tier of serious or complex fraud cases. The SFO charges offences under the most appropriate legislation in each investigation, and not only the Fraud Act.</p><br /><p>The number of individuals charged by the SFO for offences under the Fraud Act (2006) is shown in the table below.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of individuals charged under the Fraud Act 2006*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>* This type of casework information for the years prior to 2012 was not collated centrally in the same way and so the information for these years reflects the records from the time. </em></p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-01-27T14:58:18.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445835/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445835/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-01-19","Fraud: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many prosecutions have been brought under the Fraud Act 2006 in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","23175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445836","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>Details of Ministers’ meetings with external organisations are published quarterly on the Gov.uk website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;publication_type=transparency-data</a></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-08T15:46:29.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445836/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445836/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many meetings Ministers have had with representatives of Keep me Posted since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","23120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445837","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The Government has received a small number of representations from interested parties since the Government’s announcement to bring in private capital to the Green Investment Bank (GIB) in June 2015.</p><p /> <p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills met my hon Friend the Member for Beverley and Holderness (Graham Stuart) and representatives from E3G and Aldersgate Group in October, and I have met with the Member separately this month. The Government also meets GIB management regularly to discuss this and other issues.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:26:32.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445837/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445837/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent representations he has received on the proposed privatisation of the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","23237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445838","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The Government is currently exploring with the Office of National Statistics whether there is scope to implement a special share style arrangement in a way that would not amount to a form of state control.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:28:03.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445838/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445838/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent discussions he has had with the Office for National Statistics on the issuing of special shares in the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","23238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445839","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The privatisation of the Green Investment Bank will allow the company to increase its investments in the UK green economy. It will be able to raise more capital free from being on the Government balance sheet. It will also be free from State Aid restrictions on the green investments it can make.</p><p /> <p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:29:44.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445839/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445839/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the privatisation of the Green Investment Bank on the level of investment it will make in the UK green economy.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","23239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445840","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>A body such as the Green Investment Bank can only be classified to the private sector if it is not subject to significant government control over its corporate policy. That includes any control Government has over the body in terms of legislation, regulation and its contractual agreements.</p><p /> <p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:32:26.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445840/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445840/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2015 to Question 14108, whether the Government has imposed binding conditions in previous privatisations.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","23240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445841","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-27","<p>There are many differences between apprenticeships systems across EU Member States. In some countries, like England, apprenticeships are jobs, whilst in others they are training courses without employment status.</p><br /><p>Under the principle of free movement, UK citizens, like all nationals of an EU Member State, have a right to work in another, subject to all relevant employment laws.</p><br /><p>Where apprenticeships are training programmes, it is up to each member state to set the parameters for their specific programme, including offering opportunities for resident citizens of other countries.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-27T14:29:27.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445841/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445841/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Apprentices: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to ensure that UK citizens can take up apprenticeships in other EU states.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445842","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>We are supporting the efforts of the agri-tech sector to ensure that it has the skills it needs for the future. In agriculture this is led by the Agri-Skills Forum, comprising bodies such as Lantra, Landex, National Farmers Union, and the Agricultural and Horticultural Development Board, which takes a UK wide perspective of skills needs in agriculture and horticulture, and provides a direct link to employers. The Biological and Biosciences Research Council has provided £13 million of funding through its Advanced Training Programmes to support high level skills in food and farming throughout the UK.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-22T14:19:09.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445842/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445842/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Agriculture: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will take steps to ensure that best practice is shared with each of the devolved institutions on development among employers of agri-tech and skills strategies.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445843","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<p>Toy safety is fully addressed by the Toy Safety Regulations 2011. Officials are engaged with the associated standards developed and maintained through the British Standards Institute and monitoring of Trading Standards enforcement activities.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-25T15:35:04.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445843/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445843/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Toys and Games: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent steps the Government has taken to improve toy safety.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445844","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<br /><p>All products intended for use by consumers are regulated under the General Product Safety Regulations (GPSR) 2005 which implements the EU’s General Product Safety Directive (GPSD). This requires such products to be safe when placed on the market and applies to products where there is no other applicable legislation with more specific provisions on safety. This includes laser pens.</p><br /><p>In addition to the legislation, lasers sold in the UK and EU are covered by the safety standard BS EN 60825-1: 1994 Safety of Laser Products. This specifies those lasers which should be used by trained operators and therefore not suitable for use by the general public. Laser products up to 1 mW are considered safe for general consumer use.</p><br /><p>Trading Standards has the powers under the General Product Safety Regulations 2005 to remove laser products from sale to the public, which are unsafe for general consumer use. If anyone is concerned about the safety of a product they should not use it and report it to their local Trading Standards department.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-25T15:33:24.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445844/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445844/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Lasers: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what regulations govern the manufacture, import and sale of laser pens in the UK.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","23018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445845","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-27","<p>We know that the collective cost of late payment has been, and remains, a significant burden for small and medium sized businesses. Small businesses spend too much valuable time and resource chasing late payments, which impacts on their ability to invest in growth.</p><br /><p>The Department does not hold the information required to make an estimate of the collective cost to small and medium-sized businesses to recover overdue payments in each of the last five years. As late payment affects so many different types of business in different ways, no single survey gives a full picture of the impact of late payment on small and medium-sized businesses. The three sources that we look to as an indicator of late payment are the SME finance monitor, the regular BACs survey and Experian’s late payment index.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-27T17:17:28.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445845/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445845/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Small Businesses: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an estimate of the collective cost to small and medium-sized enterprises to recover overdue payments in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","23007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445846","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Government recognises the importance of prompt payment by insurers and has taken steps in the Enterprise Bill to introduce a requirement for insurers to pay all claims within a reasonable time and entitle policyholders, including small and medium sized enterprises, to damages where claims are paid late.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-27T16:07:55.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445846/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445846/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Small Businesses: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to improve the monitoring of late payments by insurance companies to claims made by small and medium-sized enterprises.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","23008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445847","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p>I assume that the Hon. Member’s question is referring to increasing the capital base of the UK Green Investment Bank (GIB), rather than increasing the capital base of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.</p><br /><p>The Government’s policy is to move the Green Investment Bank (GIB) into private ownership, minimising the Bank’s use of public funds, and where it will have the freedom to borrow and raise capital without impacting on public sector net debt.</p><br /><p>a) Green ISAs and Citizen Finance</p><p>At present, GIB has insufficient track record for the retail market. Most of its portfolio is in relatively high risk construction projects that will not provide steady returns in the short term. More importantly, GIB’s current focus is growth, for which it will need to make regular cash calls on investors, which would be hard to meet in the public markets. However there is no reason why a privatised GIB could not raise capital through Green ISAs or other forms of citizen finance in the longer term.</p><br /><p>(b) UK Pension Funds</p><p>Large scale institutional investors such as UK pension funds are likely to be interested in acquiring a stake in GIB, as part of the Government’s plans to move GIB into the private sector. GIB has already successfully attracted such investors into its managed fund for investment in Offshore Wind and other investments (e.g. Strathclyde local authority pension fund), many of whom are investing in green projects for the first time.</p><br /><p>(c) The European Investment Bank (EIB)</p><p>The EIB’s focus is on providing debt products, rather than equity investment which is where GIB expects to concentrate. It is unlikely that the EIB would make an investment in GIB itself. However, GIB is already partnering with EIB as a co-investor (such as on the recent Galloper offshore wind investment) and it may continue to do so in future.</p><br /><p>(d) Co-funding with devolved administrations</p><p>The Government’s policy is to move GIB into the private sector. Co-funding GIB with the devolved administrations would simply be another form of public sector funding.</p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:08:49.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445847/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445847/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the cost and benefits of using (a) Green ISAs and Citizen Finance, (b) UK Pension Funds, (c) the European Investment Bank and (d) co-funding with devolved administrations as a means of increasing its capital base.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","23094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445848","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-29","<p>Numbers of applicants awarded Maintenance Grants by Parliamentary Constituency in the academic year 2013/14 were provided in my reply to the hon. Member for Stalybridge and Hyde, to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-07-15/7227/" target="_blank">7227</a>.</p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-29T13:52:48.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445848/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445848/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Students: Burnley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 7 December 2015 to Question 18005, how many of the students in Burnley qualified for maintenance grants in academic year 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","23065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445849","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p>The Government considered a number of options for the Green Investment Bank’s (GIB) future but none were deemed to be as effective in meeting the Government’s objectives as the current proposals of moving GIB into majority private ownership.</p><br /><p>These alternative options were set out in our policy paper of 18 November 2015.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:23:25.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445849/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445849/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what options were considered during the decision-making process of privatisation of the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","23222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445850","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><p>The Government has made clear that we intend to sell the Green Investment Bank (GIB) as a going concern. The assets are an inherent part of that company.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-22T14:24:58.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445850/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445850/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-19","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the proposed sale of the Green Investment Bank will include all assets of the bank.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","23223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445851","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-22","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-22T12:14:02.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445851/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445851/answer","23166 FINAL.pdf","23166 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - GDP","UKSA Letter to Member - GDP","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445851/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","National Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of per capita GDP in each of the nations of the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","23166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445852","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>Individual Departments are responsible for making their own reductions to their use of paper, including as part of the Greening Government Commitments. The Cabinet Office’s own use of paper in 2015/16 to date has reduced by around 60% against the 2009/10 baseline. This reduction has been achieved including through the use of more flexible laptop-based IT and electronic records systems which means that printing requirements have reduced considerably.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-26T12:20:47.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445852/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445852/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445852/answer/previousversion/40565","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Government Departments: Paper","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to ensure a reduction in the use of paper in departments.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","23076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445853","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>The electoral registers used for the 2015 General Election contained over 400,000 more entries than the last registers published prior to the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration (IER). As such, suggestions that IER would lead to a decline in registration levels were simply incorrect.</p><p>While data is not available on the number of non-IER registered electors who voted at the 2015 General Election, the Electoral Commission found 96% of the entries on the electoral register in May 2015 were already registered under IER.</p><p>The Electoral Commission is planning to publish a report in February/March 2016 on the state of the December 2015 registers. This is expected to include data on the number of register entries and on the number of remaining non-IER registered entries removed in December.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","23087","2016-01-26T12:24:09.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445853/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445853/answer","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445853/answer/previousversion/40684","Biography information for John Penrose","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of people removed from the electoral register since December 2015 are (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","23086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445854","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>The electoral registers used for the 2015 General Election contained over 400,000 more entries than the last registers published prior to the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration (IER). As such, suggestions that IER would lead to a decline in registration levels were simply incorrect.</p><p>While data is not available on the number of non-IER registered electors who voted at the 2015 General Election, the Electoral Commission found 96% of the entries on the electoral register in May 2015 were already registered under IER.</p><p>The Electoral Commission is planning to publish a report in February/March 2016 on the state of the December 2015 registers. This is expected to include data on the number of register entries and on the number of remaining non-IER registered entries removed in December.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","23086","2016-01-26T12:24:10.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445854/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445854/answer","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445854/answer/previousversion/40687","Biography information for John Penrose","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people who voted in the 2015 General Election are not on the latest electoral register.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","23087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445855","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>In financial years 2013/14 and 2014/15 the Government has spent £72 million in the transition to Individual Electoral Registration (IER).</p><p>Of this, over £49 million was shared between all EROs in Great Britain, ensuring the transition to IER was fully funded. This included over £10 million that was allocated to local authorities specifically to boost levels of voter registration.</p><br />","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-01-25T16:53:14.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445855/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445855/answer","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445855/answer/previousversion/40688","Biography information for John Penrose","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Electoral Register: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the total cost is of the transfer to Individual Electoral Registration; and what proportion of such costs have been borne by local government.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","23088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445856","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>This information is not held and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>In line with the guidance on handling Ministerial correspondence, the Cabinet Office ensures that all correspondence, wherever possible, is personally hand-signed by the appropriate responsible Minister.</p><p>Guidance to Departments on handling correspondence is available on Gov.uk - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/441892/Cabinet_Office_Guidance_on_correspondence.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/441892/Cabinet_Office_Guidance_on_correspondence.pdf</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-26T12:21:43.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445856/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445856/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445856/answer/previousversion/40564","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Cabinet Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of ministerial letters have been signed on behalf of Ministers in their absence in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","23025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445857","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>The Government Property Unit is working closely with Oldham Council and others across Greater Manchester on future plans across the public sector estate. Oldham Council is part of the Greater Manchester Combined Authority Partnership on the One Public Estate Programme. The programme, delivered by Cabinet Office and the Local Government Association, aims to maximise local economic growth from better use of public assets. 108 councils have recently joined a third phase of the programme. Together, they expect to generate £172 million capital receipts, reduce running costs by £65 million, and create 30,000 new homes and 43,000 new jobs over the next 5 years.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-26T12:22:55.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445857/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445857/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445857/answer/previousversion/40566","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Public Sector: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will commission an assessment of the potential economic impact on Oldham of the reduction in Oldham's public estate.","true","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","23030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445858","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>There are three bodies that regulate charities in the UK; the Charity Commission for England and Wales, the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator (OSCR) and the Charity Commission for Northern Ireland. In all three jurisdictions organisations must be established for exclusively charitable purposes to be recognised and registered as charities. All applications to register an organisation as a charity are determined by whether or not an organisation meets the legal test for registration. All three bodies have robust processes for assessing any application for registration as a charity. The three regulators regularly meet to discuss areas of common concern and have provisions in their respective legislation which facilitates the exchange of information to assist and enable another to discharge their statutory functions.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-27T16:51:31.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445858/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445858/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Charities: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will ensure that charity commissions across the UK collaborate to ensure that extremist groups are unable to obtain charitable status.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445859","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>To remain the best in the world, the Civil Service needs to respond to both the challenges and opportunities of our times.The Civil Service continues to require new and different skills to respond to the fiscal environment, global competition and changes in technology, whilst at the same time delivering better services more efficiently: in short, doing more for less.</p><p>The size of the Civil Service has already reduced by 20% since March 2010 and has helped save taxpayers £2.8bn over the last Parliament. Despite this reduction in numbers, employee engagement rates were higher in 2015 than in 2010 and departments have successfully maintained delivery of our public services.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-27T13:29:13.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445859/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445859/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-19","Civil Servants: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect of civil service redundancies in the last 12 months on the effectiveness of departments' work.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","23139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445860","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Government does not have any plans to provide additional assistance to those who have purchased a home under the Help to Buy scheme, in the event of a rise in interest rates.</p><br /><p>Since April 2014, lenders have had to conduct an affordability assessment which includes a robust income and expenditure analysis. In addition, lenders must consider the impact of future interest rate increases on affordability.</p><br /><p>This ensures that mortgages are only advanced where there is a reasonable expectation that the customer can repay.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-27T16:06:46.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445860/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445860/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to provide assistance to people who have purchased homes under the Help to Buy scheme in the event that interest rates subsequently rise.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445861","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>The rural fuel duty rebate scheme offers a 5 pence per litre discount on fuel duty for fuel sold in qualifying areas. The rebate does not vary with the price of wholesale oil.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-26T17:06:39.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445861/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Fuels: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy to change the rate of fuel duty applied to certain isolated and rural areas in response to changes in oil price.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445862","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The government has received representations from a number of waste operators on this issue. We are taking views into consideration and our priority is to ensure that the LCF operates effectively and encourages money to be spent in the communities that need it.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-22T14:25:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445862/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445862/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with waste operators on the effect of planned changes to the Landfill Communities Fund.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","23195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445863","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The LCF is a tax credit scheme into which landfill operators contribute voluntarily. The impact of the changes to the LCF announced at Autumn Statement 2015 is set out in <em>Reform and value of the Landfill Communities Fund. </em>This document can be found here:</p><p><br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-22T14:24:39.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445863/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445863/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on waste operators of planned changes to the Landfill Communities Fund.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","23196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445864","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The EU’s fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (‘the Directive’) was formally adopted in June 2015, and Member States now have until June 2017 to transpose its requirements into national law. The Government plans to publish a consultation on transposition of the Directive by early spring which will run for a full 12 weeks. We will consult on areas where the Directive gives us options or discretion on how we transpose its provisions as well as areas where we can improve the UK’s anti-money laundering and counter-financing of terrorism (AML/CFT) regime.</p><br /><p>Transposition of the Directive is just one element of the Government’s comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering regime. HM Treasury and Home Office are working closely on a forthcoming Action Plan to address the issues identified in the UK’s first National Risk Assessment of Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing, in order to increase the effectiveness of the AML/CFT regime. This work is overseen jointly by Home Office and Treasury Ministers.</p><br /><p>Scrutinising all aspects of the UK’s AML/CFT regime, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Mutual Evaluation of the United Kingdom will be the ultimate test of effectiveness and will take place in the course of 2017 and 2018. The FATF Mutual Evaluation will judge both the technical compliance and effectiveness of the UK’s AML/CFT regime. But the implementation of the Directive will be key to achieving a successful evaluation, as the Directive will enact the FATF standards into UK domestic law.</p><br /><p>By undertaking this work, we are further ensuring that our anti-money laundering and counter-financing of terrorism regime is robust and sufficiently responsive to emerging threats.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-22T12:37:43.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445864/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445864/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Money Laundering: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how he plans to assess the effectiveness of the implementation in the UK of the EU Anti-Money Laundering Directive.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445865","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>Making Tax Digital will simplify tax administration for small businesses. The Government believes VAT registered businesses should have the option to provide HMRC with one update to cover both VAT and their profits-based taxes. We will consult widely on the details of Making Tax Digital during 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-22T14:41:19.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445865/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Small Businesses: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the new electronic system of quarterly income tax reporting will allow small businesses to align their reporting with VAT returns.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","23214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445866","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>Department for Work and Pensions has published estimates on salary sacrifice available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-pension-provision-survey-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-pension-provision-survey-2013</a> Estimates are not available for the number of active members who take advantage of these schemes or the loss to the National Insurance Fund.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","23083","2016-01-22T14:11:18.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445866/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445866/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Occupational Pensions: National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) employees and (b) employers have taken advantage of savings to National Insurance contributions from salary sacrifice schemes for occupational pensions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","23085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445867","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-27","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><br /><p>Information on the number of property transactions over £1m is available at the following address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/property-transactions-in-the-uk" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/property-transactions-in-the-uk</a></p><br /><p>However, recently transacted properties form only a small proportion of the total stock of properties. Many property transactions will also involve multiple purchasers. Finally, many historic purchases below £1m will now be worth more that £1m due to property price inflation. Therefore this information should be considered very much a lower boundary.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-27T15:52:39.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445867/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445867/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Property: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the number of people in the UK who own property worth over £1 million.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445868","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The government has supported a wide range of capital projects in Manchester. This includes: £533m committed to Greater Manchester through the Local Growth Fund, which will support projects such as the new Ashton town centre interchange; a £900m gainshare agreement as part of the Devolution Deal, which will support projects such as the Trafford Metrolink extension; £199m as part of the city deal over ten years for local major transport schemes; £78m for the Factory theatre and arts venue at Spending Review 2015; and £235m for the Sir Henry Royce Institute for advanced materials research at the 2014 Autumn Statement. Greater Manchester will also benefit from the North of England Rail Infrastructure programme, which is worth over £1bn.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-01-22T13:47:29.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445868/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Capital Investment: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what Government capital projects (a) have been carried out in the last and (b) are planned over the next five years in Greater Manchester; and what the (i) cost and (ii) location was and will be for each such project.","true","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","23029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445869","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The Landfill Communities Fund (LCF) is a tax credit scheme into which landfill operators contribute voluntarily. Since its introduction in 1996, the LCF has contributed over £1.4bn to community projects in areas affected by a local landfill site. However, as the LCF is a tax credit scheme, it reduces the Government's tax revenues. We therefore have an ongoing responsibility to seek value for money for the taxpayer.</p><br /><p>Our reforms aim to encourage LCF money to get to communities more quickly and use the savings to address other significant issues like waste crime. The LCF will provide £39.3 million of additional funding in 2016-17 alone. We also hope more unspent funds, which this year totalled £118 million, will reach projects as soon as possible.</p><br /><p>The impact of the changes to the LCF announced at Autumn Statement 2015 is set out in <em>Reform and value of the Landfill Communities Fund. </em>This document can be found here:</p><p><br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund/reform-and-value-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-22T14:23:41.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445869/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445869/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the likely change in the number of projects being funded through the Landfill Communities Fund if the Contributory Third Party element is removed.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","23152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445870","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The government published a summary of responses to the consultation Reform of the Landfill Communities Fund alongside Autumn Statement 2015. This document can be found here:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/479337/Summary_of_consultation_responses-as15-final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/479337/Summary_of_consultation_responses-as15-final.pdf</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-22T14:42:10.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445870/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445870/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will publish the results of its consultation into the Reform of the Landfill Communities Fund; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","23157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445871","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>The Department for Education provides capital funding to support the construction of new University Technical Colleges and allocates resource funding to support day to day running costs.</p><br /><p>This funding impacts on public sector borrowing and public sector net debt in the same way as other central government spending.</p><br />","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-01-22T14:09:07.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445871/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445871/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Public Sector: Borrowing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether (a) all and (b) part of the funding for universal technology schools count as public sector borrowing for the purposes of calculating the national debt.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","23159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445872","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>Department for Work and Pensions has published estimates on salary sacrifice available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-pension-provision-survey-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-pension-provision-survey-2013</a> Estimates are not available for the number of active members who take advantage of these schemes or the loss to the National Insurance Fund.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","23085","2016-01-22T14:11:18.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445872/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445872/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","National Insurance Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of how much has been lost to the National Insurance Fund from salary sacrifice schemes for occupational pensions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","23083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445873","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>No.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-22T10:47:11.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445873/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445873/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Holiday Accommodation: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to (a) make provision for non-EU furnished holiday let owners to benefit from the ability to offset finance costs, but not the additional reliefs that are available to EU furnished holiday let owners, or to extend the definition of a furnished holiday let to be include non-EU properties and enable access to all reliefs.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","23099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445874","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Location Programme is the result of an extended period of consultation and deliberation. The Department has taken account of a number of criteria in reaching its decisions, including the quality of local transport links, the local labour market and future workforce supply, the cost of buildings and asset value, and the need to retain the staff and skills it needs to continue its transformation. These changes will reduce HMRC’s estates costs by around £100 million a year by 2025.</p><br /><p>HMRC’s modelling estimates that the majority of staff in Scotland live within Reasonable Daily Travel of Glasgow or Edinburgh. Reasonable Daily Travel is calculated in line with established HR policies and procedures. Every worker at HMRC will have a one-to-one meeting with their manager to discuss their individual circumstances.</p><br /><p>HMRC conducted high level People Impact and Equality Assessments to inform its planning. The Department plans to update these once discussions have been held with its staff.</p><br /><p>Activities of trade union representatives are governed by long-standing agreements with departments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","22798 ; 22911 ; 22912 ; 22913 ; 22914 ; 22915","2016-01-26T14:48:19.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445874/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445874/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Revenue and Customs: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether preliminary impact assessments were carried out on the effect of the current HM Revenue and Customs Location Strategy on local tax compliance, across all heads of duty, the Scottish economy, equal opportunities in Scotland, the environment, and the individual staff whose offices are to be closed and what those assessments have indicated.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","23041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445875","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>No such research has been conducted.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-22T11:53:29.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445875/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445875/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Taxis: Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has conducted research on the total cost to the public purse of tax credits paid to private hire vehicle drivers in London in each of the last two financial years.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","23013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445876","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>Information on projects funded by the Landfill Communities Fund is published by the regulator of the fund, ENTRUST. This information is available on their website at:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.entrust.org.uk/environmental-bodies/project-search/" target="_blank">http://www.entrust.org.uk/environmental-bodies/project-search/</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-22T14:29:30.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445876/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445876/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-19","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the number and value of projects funded by the Landfill Communities Fund in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","23224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445877","Department for Education","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Government purchased the Kingsland Fire Station, 333 Kingsland Road, London E8 4DR for the sum of £16,000,000 (exclusive of VAT) from the London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority in October 2015. The site has not been sold on.</p><p> </p><p>The purchase, which was funded from the Department for Education’s budget, was made in the name of the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government; this is a long standing convention whereby the seal of the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government is held equally across all government departments and used for Land Registry Title purposes.</p><p> </p><p>We do not have the details of any gain made by the London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority from the sale of the site; that could only be answered by the Authority.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-15T16:45:28.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445877/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445877/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-19","Fire Stations: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse was of the purchase of the Kingsland Fire Station site for use by the Hackney New Primary School; and how much accrued to the public purse from the sale of that site.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","23068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445878","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-22","<p>Government interventions are reinvigorating the housing market. The number of new homes delivered last year was up by 25 per cent on the previous year, the highest year on year rise for 28 years. Completions are up and housing starts at their highest annual level since 2007, with more than 277,000 affordable homes delivered since April 2010 .</p><p>We have announced a doubling of the housing budget to more than £20 billion over the next five years to support the largest housing programme by any Government since the 1970’s</p><p>Between 2000/01 and 2012/13, the Housing Benefit bill more than doubled to £24 billion and the cost to the taxpayer increased 50%.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-22T14:56:59.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445878/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445878/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-19","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the overall effect of changes to housing legislation and housing-related benefits which have come into force since 2010.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","23149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445879","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Government is on target to deliver access to superfast broadband for 95% of UK premises by December 2017, and to extend coverage beyond that as far as possible. As the Prime Minister announced last autumn, the government proposes that by the end of this parliament people should have a legal right to request access to a good level of broadband speed, no matter where they live.</p><p /> <p>The honourable member will be pleased to hear that in her Great Grimsby constituency, 96 per cent of homes and businesses can already access superfast broadband - and it is estimated that coverage will rise to98 per cent by the end of 2017. Additional funding sources, including the £129 million of gainshare funding that BT will return in response to the high levels of take-up being achieved, will allow coverage to be extended further in Great Grimsby and the rest of the area covered by the North Lincolnshire broadband project.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","23147","2016-01-29T13:35:23.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445879/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445879/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Housing Associations: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of housing association residents have access to the internet at home.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","23146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445880","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Government is on target to deliver access to superfast broadband for 95% of UK premises by December 2017, and to extend coverage beyond that as far as possible. As the Prime Minister announced last autumn, the government proposes that by the end of this parliament people should have a legal right to request access to a good level of broadband speed, no matter where they live.</p><p /> <p>The honourable member will be pleased to hear that in her Great Grimsby constituency, 96 per cent of homes and businesses can already access superfast broadband - and it is estimated that coverage will rise to98 per cent by the end of 2017. Additional funding sources, including the £129 million of gainshare funding that BT will return in response to the high levels of take-up being achieved, will allow coverage to be extended further in Great Grimsby and the rest of the area covered by the North Lincolnshire broadband project.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","23146","2016-01-29T13:35:23.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445880/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445880/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Social Rented Housing: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of local authority social housing residents have access to the internet at home.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","23147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445881","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-22","<p>The number of disabled social housing tenants (including housing association tenants) who have moved out of their property in each year since 2005-6 is shown in the attached table.</p><p>These figures show that the number of social tenants who have moved has fluctuated over time, but the proportion of social renters who have moved has remained relatively constant.</p><p>The reasons for these moves are not known although we expect some disabled social tenants will have moved to better (e.g. adapted) accommodation. Some will have moved from a different tenure i.e.from owner occupation or the private rented sector), while others will have moved from another social housing property.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","23121","2016-01-22T15:19:00.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445881/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445881/answer","PQ 23148.docx","PQ 23148.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445881/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-19","Social Rented Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many disabled social housing residents have moved out of their property in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","23148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445882","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-22","<p>There is no specific council tax discount or exemption for foster carers. However, councils have powers to introduce discretionary discounts. We are aware of two authorities, in Camden and Waltham Forest, who are using those powers to offer discounts in their areas.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-22T13:16:18.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445882/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445882/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-19","Foster Care: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities offer a council tax (a) exemption and (b) discount to foster carers within their area.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","23145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445883","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-22","<p>As independent providers of social housing, it is for housing associations to decide on the level of services they wish to provide to their tenants.</p><p>Housing associations are regulated by the Social Housing Regulator against its standards framework; where there are issues of non-compliance with the regulatory standards the Regulator has powers to intervene.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-22T13:17:20.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445883/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445883/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-19","Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of changes in the level of services provided by housing associations to tenants since 2013.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","23150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445884","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-22","<p>The number of disabled social housing tenants (including housing association tenants) who have moved out of their property in each year since 2005-6 is shown in the attached table.</p><p>These figures show that the number of social tenants who have moved has fluctuated over time, but the proportion of social renters who have moved has remained relatively constant.</p><p>The reasons for these moves are not known although we expect some disabled social tenants will have moved to better (e.g. adapted) accommodation. Some will have moved from a different tenure i.e.from owner occupation or the private rented sector), while others will have moved from another social housing property.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","23148","2016-01-22T15:19:00.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445884/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445884/answer","PQ 23148.docx","PQ 23148.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445884/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-19","Housing Associations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many disabled housing association residents moved out of their property in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","23121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445885","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-26","<p>A Government call to evidence on switching principles has recently closed. We have committed to legislating for easier switching in the Communications markets, and we are now working with Ofcom to progress this.</p><p>Ofcom’s assessment of the costs and benefits of implementing the enhanced process are set out in Chapter 9 at<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/consultations/consumer-switching-review/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/consultations/consumer-switching-review/</a>.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-26T15:16:49.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445885/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445885/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment (a) his Department and (b) Ofcom have made of the effectiveness of the gaining provider-led notification of transfer process for broadband since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445886","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-26","<p>The Authority for TV On Demand (ATVOD) are currently preparing the report &quot;Provision of Video on Demand Access Services 2015&quot;. This report, combined with meetings with broadcasters, content providers and platform operators, will inform Government's next steps.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-26T15:15:40.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445886/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445886/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Video on Demand: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government will set out for broadcasters the level of progress it expects to see on the provision of subtitles and audio-descriptions for on-demand content before it reviews the legislation in that area.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","23040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445887","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-26","<p>The UK is one of the most advanced digital countries in the world. The Government is currently developing a Digital Strategy, to be published later this year, which will set out the actions we will take so we continue to lead the world in embracing the benefits of digital technology in our government, economy and society.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has provided support and engagement to Code for America through a series of visits and information sharing activities as it has developed its programme, and continues to work with relevant international organisations to share best practice as appropriate to support and promote the UK's status as a world leader in digital government.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-26T10:22:42.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445887/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445887/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Code for America","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the role of the Code for America programme and its applicability to the UK.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","23160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445889","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-27","<p>We believe that everyone should have equal access to arts and culture - having a disability should not be a barrier to enjoying Britain's awe-inspiring cultural treasures. That is why we are working with venues and organisations representing disabled people to identify barriers to access, while at the same time seeing how we can share examples of best practice and what more cultural venues need to do to be accessible to people with disabilities. We support the work of Attitude is Everything, which works with audiences, artists and the music industry to improve deaf and disabled people’s access to live events. I also recently held a roundtable meeting with Justin Tomlinson, Minister for Disabled People, to look at access to cultural venues and events for disabled people.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-27T14:06:29.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445889/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445889/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Music: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the number of spaces available for disabled people in music venues; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John Mc Nally","23066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445890","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-27","<p>The location of Ofcom departments and its offices is a matter for Ofcom, who are independent from Government.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-27T15:27:05.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445890/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445890/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Ofcom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of relocation of Ofcom departments from London to other areas of the country on Ofcom's ability to maintain its service standards.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","23000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445891","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>BDUK models broadband coverage using a combination of commercial and BDUK project data mapped against UK postcodes.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-29T13:33:35.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445891/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445891/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on what basis Broadband Delivery UK (BDUK) provides forecasts for the rollout of BDUK-funded broadband infrastructure in local areas.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","23015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445892","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) is the primary regulator in relation to the protection of personal data - its powers are set out in the Data Protection Act (1998) and the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations (2003). Ofcom has responsibilities in relation to network security under Sections 105A to 105D of the Communications Act (2003), which place an obligation on providers of telecoms networks and services to take appropriate measures to protect their security and resilience. Ofcom and the ICO have agreed that the ICO will lead on any personal data protection issues which may also fall within the scope of s105A. As with all matters of responsibility for regulation, these arrangements are kept under review.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-29T13:36:48.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445892/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445892/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-19","Ofcom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what responsibilities Ofcom has for (a) data protection, (b) consumer rights relating to data and (c) data markets; and what plans he has to review those responsibilities.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","23016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445893","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>The UK is committed to the security of Lebanon, including helping the Lebanese state secure its borders. From 2012-2015 we used over £30 million to help the Lebanese army raise and equip three Land Border Regiments (LBRs) deployed along the border with Syria. The project provides the LBRs with border towers, non-lethal equipment, mentoring and training. This has had a direct effect in mitigating contagion from the war in Syria. The border regiments successfully repel frequent attacks by Daesh on Lebanese territory. 75% of the Syria-Lebanon border will be under state control by March 2016, and the rest will be further secured with the establishment of a fourth LBR in financial year 2016-17.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-26T15:42:46.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445893/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445893/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Lebanon: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has made of the effect equipment gifted to the Lebanese armed forces between 2012 and 2015 on that country's ability to secure its border with Syria against (a) the spread of the Syrian conflict, (b) the movement of Hezbollah fighters supporting the Assad Regime and (c) the movement of Daesh fighters.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","23071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445894","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p><br></p><p>I have taken help by Veterans UK to mean assistance provided by the Veterans UK Welfare Service. The Veterans Welfare Service provides Veterans and their families' with free and confidential advice on a wide range of issues.</p><br /><p>Regrettably, the information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><br /><p>However, the total number of visits to Veterans from the Veterans UK Welfare Service since 01 January 2010 to 20 January 2016 in the Pendle, Lancashire and North West district, are set out below.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>District</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>*Number of Visits</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pendle</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lancashire</p></td><td><p>1,870</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West(1)</p></td><td><p>7,240</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>(1) This figure incorporates the Pendle and Lancashire districts.</p><br /><p>*In line with departmental policy, values have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><br /><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-26T15:42:09.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445894/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445894/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Veterans: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many veterans in (a) Pendle, (b) Lancashire and (c) the North West have been helped by Veterans UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","23072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445895","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>For national security reasons, we do not specify how much Conflict Pool and Conflict Stability and Security Fund has been allocated to other states fighting Daesh. I can confirm that in Iraq, we are making a £2 million contribution to the UN Funding Facility for Immediate Stabilisation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-27T15:05:04.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445895/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445895/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-19","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much of the (a) conflict pool and (b) conflict security stability fund has been allocated to other states fighting Daesh since 2014.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","23069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445896","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>Your question concerning how much Veterans UK has spent on providing support to Veterans has been interpreted to mean assistance provided by the Veterans UK Welfare Service.</p><p>This information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-26T15:37:56.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445896/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445896/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Veterans UK: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much Veterans UK has spent on providing support to veterans in (a) Pendle, (b) Lancashire and (c) the North West since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","23070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445897","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-22","<br /><p>In the last 12 months there have been no unauthorised incursions by any foreign military aircraft into sovereign UK air space, which projects 12 miles off shore or to mutually agreed mid-points between adjacent nations over narrow straits such as the Straits of Dover. Russian military aircraft activity has remained in international airspace at all times. The UK civil air traffic region and the NATO Air Policing Area, for which the UK have responsibility for monitoring, include large areas of international air space through which foreign military traffic may legally transit.</p><br /><br />","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-22T13:30:32.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445897/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445897/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Russia: Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many times unsanctioned Russian military aircraft have been detected entering UK airspace in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","23095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445898","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>It is recognised that harbours in the UK and around the world vary in size, and that not all are able to accommodate all classes of ships due to constraints such as navigation channels, water depth, tidal movements, tug and pilotage arrangements, and berthing facilities. There are, however, a sufficient number of harbours and ports both at home and overseas that our ships can access, or could anchor in the vicinity of, to receive the necessary support.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-26T16:34:59.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445898/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445898/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Navy: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will take steps to ensure that harbours can accommodate any new vessels built for use by the Royal Navy.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445899","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence together with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, the Home Office and the Department for Transport, published the UK National Strategy for Maritime Security (NSMS) in May 2014. This cross-Government paper encompasses all aspects of the UK's maritime domain, including the Merchant Navy whose cooperation, as part of the Red Ensign Group, is important to maintaining our national security and prosperity.</p><p>The Royal Fleet Auxiliary plays a key role in maritime security either by directly supporting Royal Navy ships on operations or, occasionally, conducting operations in their own right. Her Majesty's Government places great importance on all maritime capabilities, with the NSMS setting out the whole-of-Government approach required to secure the seas and oceans that Britain depends on.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-27T16:11:30.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445899/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445899/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Merchant Shipping and Royal Fleet Auxiliary: National Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the importance of the (a) Merchant Navy and (b) Royal Fleet Auxiliary to the security of the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445900","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<p>Women already serve in a variety of roles with front line units including pilots, submariners, medics, fire support team commanders, military intelligence operators, counter improvised explosive device operators and dog handlers. They have made and continue to make a valuable contribution to recent and current operations including Afghanistan.</p><p>Women are currently excluded from serving in Ground Close Combat roles; the Infantry and Royal Armoured Corps, the Royal Marines and the Royal Air Force Regiment. The Prime Minister stated on 20 December 2015 that he wants to see all roles in the Armed Forces opened up to women in 2016 and further physiological research currently under way will inform a final decision in mid-2016.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-26T15:45:44.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445900/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445900/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Armed Forces: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what training his Department provides for women to enable them to serve in combat on the front line.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445901","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<p>We welcome the recent progress towards the formation of a Government of National Accord in Libya. We are considering, with partner nations, how we can best support a Libyan Government once it is established, including capacity building and security sector reform.</p><p>We are also training two Libyan Officer Cadets who are due to commission from Sandhurst later this year after successfully completing their training programme in the UK which started in April 2014.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-26T15:45:14.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445901/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445901/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Libya: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assistance the Government has given to the Libyan government for training Libyan army personnel.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445902","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>The Ministry of Defence has received no such representations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-26T16:19:36.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445902/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445902/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-19","Rolls-Royce Marine Power Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent representations he has received in favour of Government involvement in any part of the running of departments or divisions of Rolls Royce connected to that company's production of the Nuclear Reactor Component of the Successor Programme.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","23128"
