"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>All funding for the Magna Carta Fund for Human Rights and Democracy will come from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s budget.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-01-27T17:35:28.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445956/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445956/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-19","Magna Carta Fund for Human Rights and Democracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the announcement of 19 January 2016 of the launch of the £10 million Magna Carta Fund for Human Rights and Democracy, how much of the additional funding in that area will come from the budget of (a) his Department and (b) the Department for International Development.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","23168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Government’s approach to all states which retain the death penalty is to focus first on suspension of its use as the key step towards permanent abolition. We take a pragmatic approach to achieving that goal. We welcome reforms which improve legal procedures, reduce the number of capital crimes or mitigate some of the cruelties inherent to the death penalty. We fund projects which educate the judiciary, promote reform, mount legal challenges to death penalty systems and stimulate public debate. We engage diplomatically with retentionist states to ensure they are aware of the compelling arguments against the death penalty and of the UK Government’s opposition to any execution. Our assessment is that these approaches are stimulating a long-term movement by states towards abolition.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-01-27T17:39:16.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445957/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-19","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether it is his policy to take steps towards repeal of the death penalty in states which hold the death penalty.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","23192"
