"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445408","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<p><strong></strong></p><p>The Government does not hold information on the value of the curry industry, the number of curry houses, trends in the number of curry houses or the number of curry chefs.</p><br /><p>Official statistics carry figures on the value and number of restaurants, takeaways and other food service businesses in general, but do not detail specific types of food being served. Similarly while the number of chefs and catering staff will be estimated there is no consideration of their specialisation in terms of cuisine.</p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","22780 ; 22781 ; 22782","2016-01-25T15:38:10.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445408/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445408/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the number of curry chefs working in the UK in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","22783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445409","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-26","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>Information on the number of Apprentices working in the curry industry is not available.</p><p /> <p>Apprenticeship starts by Sector Framework and Standard are published as a supplementary table (first link) to a Statistical First Release (second link).</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/477738/apprenticeships-starts-by-sase-framework.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/477738/apprenticeships-starts-by-sase-framework.xls</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held</a></p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-26T14:29:14.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445409/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445409/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Catering: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of apprentices working in the curry industry.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","22784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445410","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-26","<p><strong></strong></p><p>We have a range of measures to help support all businesses, including the curry industry. The British Business Bank programmes are supporting £2.4 billion of finance to over 40,000 smaller businesses. Included within this is the Start-Up Loans programme, which has provided over 34,000 loans worth over £187 million. We have saved businesses £10 billion of red tape and we have extended small business rate relief.</p><p /> <p>Employer-led Trailblazers are currently leading the way in the design and delivery of new more rigorous apprenticeship standards to support a range of sectors. Standards relating to several chef roles have already been developed and these are intended to cover specialisms such as Indian cuisine.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-26T16:40:27.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445410/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445410/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to support the curry industry.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","22785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445411","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>My Rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has regular discussions with the Home Secretary on a wide variety of issues.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-08T15:41:52.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445411/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445411/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Catering: Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the Home Secretary on amending immigration rules to support the curry industry.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","22768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445412","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-16","<p>The ‘Centres of Excellence in Asian Cookery’ pilots were organised by People 1<sup>st</sup>, which was operating on behalf of the Hospitality Guild, which received funding from the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UKCES) through their grant with BIS. People 1<sup>st </sup>reported that during the period of the pilot (October 2011 to September 2013), 79 people started training at the Centres of Excellence for Asian and Oriental cuisine, out of which 46 completed the pre-employment course, 22 completed work experience and 7 moved onto an apprenticeship.</p><p> </p><p>£205,961 was provided to fund the Asian Cookery campaign. In total, UKCES allocated £1,745,785 to create the Hospitality Guild and to promote skills training, apprenticeships and innovation in the hospitality industry through a range of measures. These included apprenticeships as chefs, baristas, bar staff and hotel management, training provider accreditation, work placements and launching the Hospitality Guild Portal where careers tools, an employer guide and a vacancy matching service can be accessed.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","22770 ; 22771","2016-02-16T09:02:44.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445412/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445412/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Hospitality Guild: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on how many people attended the Hospitality Guild's centres of excellence in Asian cookery in each of the last three years; and how many such people successfully completed that training.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","22769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445413","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<br /> <br /><p>Government funding for the Green Investment Bank (GIB) for the 2016-17 period and beyond has now been announced as part of the current spending review. This is a good settlement for GIB and provides what GIB management wanted by allowing for 100% funding of GIB’s investments to the point of majority sale, assuming a sale in the next financial year.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-21T17:32:54.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445413/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445413/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Green Investment Bank: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2015 to Question 8988, whether the Government has taken a decision on the funding of the Green Investment Bank's business activity in future years.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","22804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445414","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-01","<p>The table below provides information regarding HEFCE funding for each of the last 5 years to support students from disadvantaged backgrounds through the Student Opportunity Fund. HEFCE has not yet made decisions for future years. Its decisions will be made in the light of its overall grant settlements from Government.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Since 2012, universities have been expected to take greater responsibility for widening access. Institutions wishing to charge fees above the basic rate are required to have Access Agreements with the Director of Fair Access showing what more they will do to widen access. In 2014/15, institutions spent £713 million on Access Agreements, up from £404 million in 2009/10.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Hefce funding to support students from disadvantaged backgrounds through Student Opportunity Fund, £’000</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Academic Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Student Opportunity Fund Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>368,127</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>365,601</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>332,002</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>367,846</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>378,648</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In addition, a total of £116mn was provided between 2011 and 2014 through the Access to Learning Fund, and a total of £198mn between 2011 and 2016 through the National Scholarship Programme.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-01T15:28:50.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445414/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445414/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Students: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on Higher Education Funding Council for England spending to support students from disadvantaged backgrounds in each of the last five years; and what the expected spend will be by that Council on supporting such students in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","22794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445415","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<br /><p>The support available under the student finance system is reviewed annually.</p><br /><p>An Equality Analysis of changes to the support package for full-time students in 2016/17 was published on the GOV.UK website on 3 December 2015.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-21T17:39:53.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445415/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445415/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Students: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of the level of maintenance support for undergraduate students; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","22795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445416","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<p><br></p><p>As set out in the answer to question 22471 on 18 January, the Government is moving UK Green Investment Bank plc (GIB) into private ownership so it can continue operating in the same way it does now only funded with private capital rather than relying on taxpayers’ support. The detailed background and supporting case for this move was set out in the policy statement we published on 18 November. Decisions on the proposed sale are being taken in accordance with best practice to ensure all available options are properly examined in a detailed business case and that a robust valuation process is followed. The process does not involve preparation of an environmental impact assessment as we do not envisage any direct environmental or regulatory impacts of a majority sale of GIB, or changes to pre-existing policy goals for GIB.</p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-21T17:42:19.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445416/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445416/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Green Investment Bank: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the Government has undertaken an environmental impact assessment of its policy to privatise the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","22816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445417","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2016-01-26","<p><del class="ministerial">Eleven financial penalties have been imposed on employers for aggravated breach of employment law, under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013, since its introduction on 6 April 2014.</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">To date, four penalties have been paid and seven remain unpaid. Enforcement action is currently being considered for the outstanding penalties.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Twelve financial penalties have been imposed on employers for aggravated breach of employment law, under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013, since its introduction on 6 April 2014.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">To date, six penalties have been paid and six remain unpaid. Enforcement action is currently being considered for the outstanding penalties.</ins></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-26T14:33:10.433Z","2016-02-11T17:56:31.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445417/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445417/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445417/answer/previousversion/41148","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Employment Tribunals Service: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many financial penalties have been imposed on respondent employers under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013; and how many such penalties (a) have been paid and (b) remain unpaid.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","22831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445418","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<p>Statistics showing the number and value of Maintenance Grants awarded to English applicants for study at UK providers are published annually by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release ‘<em>Student Support for Higher Education in England</em>’.</p><br /><p>The latest publication covering the last five academic years can be found here:</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx" target="_blank">&quot;http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded/england-higher-education.aspx&quot;</a></p><br /><p>Publications covering previous academic years can be found here:</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/full-catalogue-of-official-statistics/student-support-for-higher-education-in-england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/full-catalogue-of-official-statistics/student-support-for-higher-education-in-england.aspx</a></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-21T17:44:19.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445418/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445418/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) number and (b) value of maintenance grants issued in each of the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","22849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445419","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>Since the launch of the National Living Wage website we have achieved the following:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Week</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Page views</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Visitors</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 6 to 12 (launched on the 7<sup>th</sup>)</p></td><td><p>8,667</p></td><td><p>7,789</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dec 13 to Dec 19</p></td><td><p>10,235</p></td><td><p>9,207</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 20 to 26</p></td><td><p>6,241</p></td><td><p>5,003</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 27 to January 2</p></td><td><p>7,153</p></td><td><p>5,742</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 3 to 9</p></td><td><p>17,900</p></td><td><p>13,853</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 10 to 16</p></td><td><p>22,945</p></td><td><p>17,794</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 17 to 19 (partial week as answered on Jan 20)</p></td><td><p>16,312</p></td><td><p>12,641</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-16T12:06:09.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445419/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445419/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Living Wage: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 14 January 2016 to Question 20599, how many (a) page views and (b) visitors the www.livingwage.gov.uk website has had in each week since its launch.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","22839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445420","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<p>The Green Investment Bank (GIB) estimates that approximately 5700 jobs have been created during the construction phases of their projects and approximately 1000 jobs have been created during the operational phase of their projects. Apprenticeship numbers are not recorded separately from other jobs but any apprenticeship roles would be included in the figures mentioned above.</p><p /> <p>We would expect a privatised GIB to continue to monitor the green and other benefits of their investments, such as job creation.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-21T17:25:17.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445420/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445420/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Green Investment Bank: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2015 to Question 3892, how many (a) jobs and (b) apprenticeships were created by each Green Investment Bank (GIB) investment; and whether he plans to monitor the performance of a privatised GIB in creating jobs and apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","22863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445421","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-21","<p>The Government does not currently hold information centrally on how many companies have expressed an interest in trading with Iran.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-21T17:30:27.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445421/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445421/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Overseas Trade: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many companies based in Scotland have expressed an interest in trading with Iran; and what steps the Government is taking to increase trade between Scotland and Iran.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","22885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445422","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-21","<br /><p>The Garden Bridge Trust is a body dedicated to creating the London Garden Bridge and to advancing public education and training in horticulture and arboriculture on the Garden. It is registered as a UK charity.</p><br /><p>The UK corporation tax system provides for relief to companies for qualifying donations or payments to charities.</p><br /><p>Hence, donations made by corporates to the Garden Bridge Trust will be deductible from their corporation tax liability in the limits set out by legislation.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-21T17:16:00.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445422/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445422/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Garden Bridge","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether donations to the proposed London Garden Bridge by corporate bodies are tax deductible.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","22892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445423","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-22","<p>A policy costing for the changes to the LCF announced at Autumn Statement 2015 was published in <em>Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015: policy costings</em>. This document is available at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-and-autumn-statement-2015-documents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-and-autumn-statement-2015-documents</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-22T14:40:11.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445423/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445423/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the financial effects of removing contributory third party funding from the Landfill Communities Fund.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","22873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445424","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>Information on the financial contribution of the solar power industry to the UK economy is not available. Solar electricity generation has been incentivised by the support under the Renewables Obligation, Contract for Difference and the Small Scale Feed in Tariff schemes. Information on private sectorinvestment from 2010-2014 is obtainable from the March 2015 DECC publication, “Delivering UK Energy Investment“ which is available here https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/419024/DECC_LowCarbonEnergyReport.pdf</p><p>The Office for National Statistics are due to publish a sector report on solar in February 2016 as part of their Low Carbon and Renewable Economy Survey for 2014 which is likely to provide further relevant information.</p><br />","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-26T17:04:23.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445424/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445424/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Solar Power: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the financial contribution of the solar power industry to the UK economy in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014 and (f) 2015.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445425","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-26T15:03:09.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445425/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445425/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","World Economy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions his Department has had with Andrew Roberts from the Royal Bank of Scotland to discuss the state of the world economy.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445426","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment on any ongoing investigations. This is an operational matter for the FCA which is an independent regulator. I have transferred this question across to them and they will respond fully in due course.</p><br /><p>The Government is clear that any attempted manipulation of any financial market is completely unacceptable. The integrity of the City matters to the economy of Britain, and that is why the Government is taking action at home, in Europe, and globally, to ensure that this behaviour is punished and that similar scandals cannot occur again.</p><br /><p>The Government has taken a number of steps to strengthen financial regulation in the UK. These include introducing the Senior Managers and Certification Regime to provide for effective regulation of individual conduct and accountability in the banking sector. The Bank of England and Financial Services Bill, now before the House of Commons, will extend this regime to cover all authorised financial services firms, including dealers in securities and other non-banks which may engage in high-frequency trading (HFT).</p><br /><p>The Government has supported the European Union (EU) Markets in Financial Instruments Directive 2 (MiFID 2), which from 2017 will alter the regulatory landscape in relation to automated trading including HFT. As part of this, HFT firms will be required to disclose information concerning their trading activities to their regulator in order to increase the regulatory supervision of these markets.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","22824","2016-01-26T14:58:05.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445426/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445426/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many high-frequency traders have been investigated by the Financial Conduct Authority for predatory practices.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445427","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>HM Treasury is not conducting a feasibility study into future connections between UK and Chinese stock markets. The London Stock Exchange Group and the Shanghai Stock Exchange are carrying out a feasibility study on a stock market connection.</p><br /><p>HM Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments, including those in China, and their impact on the UK as part of the normal process of policy development.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-26T14:59:06.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445427/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445427/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Stock Market: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the recent fall in Chinese stocks on Government plans to explore connecting the UK and Chinese markets.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445428","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments, including those in China, and their impact on the UK as part of the normal process of policy development.</p><br /><p>The Chancellor has warned that “last year was the worst for global growth since the crash and this year opens with a dangerous cocktail of new threats from around the world.” As one of the most open trading economies in the world with a large financial sector, we have to recognise that the UK is not immune to the continued problems being experienced in the world economy.</p><br /><p>We should not let this put us off engaging with China. As the Chancellor said while leading the UK’s Economic and Financial Dialogue with China in September 2015, both countries: “have a shared commitment to laying the foundations for stronger, more productive economies that can weather periods of uncertainty. At the same time, we need to continue to pursue the longer-term reform challenges that both our governments are pursuing.”</p><br /><p>The Bank of England’s 2015 stress tests modelled a severe slowdown in commodities and emerging markets. No banks were required to submit revised capital plans following the stress tests. This provides further reassurance that the UK’s banking system is capable of weathering future financial storms both at home and abroad.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-26T17:27:50.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445428/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445428/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Stock Market: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to protect UK businesses, the economy and the City from turbulence in Chinese stock markets.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445429","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment on any ongoing investigations. This is an operational matter for the FCA which is an independent regulator. I have transferred this question across to them and they will respond fully in due course.</p><br /><p>The Government is clear that any attempted manipulation of any financial market is completely unacceptable. The integrity of the City matters to the economy of Britain, and that is why the Government is taking action at home, in Europe, and globally, to ensure that this behaviour is punished and that similar scandals cannot occur again.</p><br /><p>The Government has taken a number of steps to strengthen financial regulation in the UK. These include introducing the Senior Managers and Certification Regime to provide for effective regulation of individual conduct and accountability in the banking sector. The Bank of England and Financial Services Bill, now before the House of Commons, will extend this regime to cover all authorised financial services firms, including dealers in securities and other non-banks which may engage in high-frequency trading (HFT).</p><br /><p>The Government has supported the European Union (EU) Markets in Financial Instruments Directive 2 (MiFID 2), which from 2017 will alter the regulatory landscape in relation to automated trading including HFT. As part of this, HFT firms will be required to disclose information concerning their trading activities to their regulator in order to increase the regulatory supervision of these markets.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","22825","2016-01-26T14:58:05.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445429/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445429/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Financial Markets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government has taken to prevent predatory high-frequency trading.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445430","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Location Programme is the result of an extended period of consultation and deliberation. The Department has taken account of a number of criteria in reaching its decisions, including the quality of local transport links, the local labour market and future workforce supply, the cost of buildings and asset value, and the need to retain the staff and skills it needs to continue its transformation. These changes will reduce HMRC’s estates costs by around £100 million a year by 2025.</p><br /><p>HMRC’s modelling estimates that the majority of staff in Scotland live within Reasonable Daily Travel of Glasgow or Edinburgh. Reasonable Daily Travel is calculated in line with established HR policies and procedures. Every worker at HMRC will have a one-to-one meeting with their manager to discuss their individual circumstances.</p><br /><p>HMRC conducted high level People Impact and Equality Assessments to inform its planning. The Department plans to update these once discussions have been held with its staff.</p><br /><p>Activities of trade union representatives are governed by long-standing agreements with departments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","22911 ; 22912 ; 22913 ; 22914 ; 22915 ; 23041","2016-01-26T14:48:19.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445430/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445430/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Revenue and Customs: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of HM Revenue and Customs staff in Scotland are deemed to be within reasonable daily travel distance of the two proposed regional centres; and on what assumptions those estimates were based.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","22798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445431","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-21","<p>The proportion of people who are able to afford to rent or buy a home at a point in time is a function of macroeconomic and a number of other factors around which there is a high degree of uncertainty. As such, we do not believe such an assessment would prove to be reliable.</p><p>The Department publishes data on housing costs and income as part of the English Housing Survey. The latest survey, for 2013-14, shows that in England the proportion of income spent on housing costs was 18% for mortgagers, 29% for social renters, and 34% for private renters. The full report is available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/461439/EHS_Households_2013-14.pdf</p><p>In respect of housing need in London, it is for the Mayor of London, working with London Boroughs, to identify and plan for the market and affordable housing needs in London.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-21T17:09:37.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445431/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445431/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-18","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 19817, for what reasons his Department does not produce estimates of the proportion of people who will be unable to afford to rent or buy a home in London in 2016.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","22789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445432","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<p>All student loans issued on behalf of government are issued by the Student Loans Company. Statistics on the loans issued annually by the Student Loans Company are published separately for BIS and each devolved administration in the Statistical First Releases available at the link:</p><p /> <p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/financial-support-awarded.aspx</a></p><p /> <p>The outstanding balance for Income Contingent Repayment (ICR) Loans issued by the Student Loans Company is published separately for BIS and each devolved administration in the Statistical First Releases available at the link:</p><p /> <p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment.aspx</a></p><p /> <p>Students starting courses prior to 1998 were eligible for “mortgage style” loans—such loans have since been sold to independent companies who now administer the collection of loan repayments, but do not issue loans. BIS is not able to state the amount currently owed to these companies. The companies in question are Finance for Higher Education Ltd, Honours Trustee Ltd and Erudio Student Loans Ltd.</p><p /> <br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-25T16:38:33.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445432/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445432/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-18","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what amount of loans (a) has been issued by and (b) is owed to each company responsible for issuing and collecting student loans.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","22757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445433","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-25","<p>In July 2012 the Department for Communities and Local Government published a post – legislative assessment of the then Government’s Rating (Empty Properties) Act 2007 which can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/236094/8411.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/236094/8411.pdf</a></p><p>We do not hold the figures requested. Details of empty property rate relief granted can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/417995/150326_Table_2_-_3_years.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/417995/150326_Table_2_-_3_years.xlsx</a></p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","22937","2016-01-25T15:49:20.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445433/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445433/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-18","Rating (Empty Properties) Act 2007","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what savings his Department has made as a result of the Rating (Empty Properties) Act 2007 in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","22963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445434","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>The London Stock Exchange Group and the Shanghai Stock Exchange are carrying out a feasibility study on a stock market connection, and will determine the date for completion in due course.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-26T15:00:53.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445434/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445434/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Stock Market: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the feasibility study on the possibility of connecting UK and Chinese stock markets will be completed.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","22964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445435","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs do not hold the requested data.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-26T14:51:05.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445435/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445435/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 11 January 2016 to Question 20785, what proportion of tax credit recipients had their credits erroneously withdrawn when their children progressed into post-16 education in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","22971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445436","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-21","<p>The Government estimates that the increase in the personal allowance to £11,000 in 2016/17 will reduce the income tax liability for 29.2 million individuals in the UK.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-21T17:16:51.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445436/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445436/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Income Tax: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish an estimate of how many people in each region and parliamentary constituency will benefit from the rise in the income tax personal allowance to £11,000 on 6 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","22893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445437","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-21","<p>There is no body with formal responsibility for providing advice to UK banks and building societies offering first charge mortgages on properties outside of the UK.</p><br /><p>The regulation of first charge mortgages in a territory outside of the UK is a matter for the legal and regulatory framework in that territory.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-21T12:25:30.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445437/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445437/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Mortgages: Occupied Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 6 January 2016 to Question 21322, which body is responsible for providing advice to UK banks and building societies offering mortgages on properties in the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","22898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445438","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has strict brand guidelines around the use of its logo. Only in very occasional circumstances will it allow a third-party supplier to use the HMRC logo alongside its own, when it is providing direct services to customers on behalf of HMRC.</p><br /><p>HMRC is among the most phished brands in the world and is constantly vigilant against the fraudulent use of its logo and brand. Where such misuse is identified, HMRC will take a range of actions to protect customers from fraud, including:</p><ul><li>demanding the removal of the logo by the third party</li><li>legal action</li><li>working with internet service providers to remove websites</li><li>proactively publicising to customers when new phishing websites are found <ul><li>providing publicity advice to keep safe online.</li></ul><br><p>Since July 2014, HMRC has closed 22,210 fake websites.</p><br> <p>The Government also provides guidance on gov.uk on the types of genuine communication that customers can expect from the department.</li></ul>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-21T17:13:49.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445438/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445438/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Revenue and Customs: Logos","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what guidance his Department provides to partner organisations on using the HM Revenue and Customs logo in such a way as to make it clear to consumers the difference between legitimate partner organisations and scam websites.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","22870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445439","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-22","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not publish forecasts of house building.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-22T13:27:36.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445439/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445439/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-18","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many houses he expects to be built in the UK in 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","22902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445440","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Location Programme is the result of an extended period of consultation and deliberation. The Department has taken account of a number of criteria in reaching its decisions, including the quality of local transport links, the local labour market and future workforce supply, the cost of buildings and asset value, and the need to retain the staff and skills it needs to continue its transformation. These changes will reduce HMRC’s estates costs by around £100 million a year by 2025.</p><br /><p>HMRC’s modelling estimates that the majority of staff in Scotland live within Reasonable Daily Travel of Glasgow or Edinburgh. Reasonable Daily Travel is calculated in line with established HR policies and procedures. Every worker at HMRC will have a one-to-one meeting with their manager to discuss their individual circumstances.</p><br /><p>HMRC conducted high level People Impact and Equality Assessments to inform its planning. The Department plans to update these once discussions have been held with its staff.</p><br /><p>Activities of trade union representatives are governed by long-standing agreements with departments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","22798 ; 22911 ; 22913 ; 22914 ; 22915 ; 23041","2016-01-26T14:48:19.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445440/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/445440/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-18","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the effect of the HM Revenue and Customs Location Strategy on future tax revenues.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","22912"
